onal focus on divine persons, Hart reimagines the Trinity in terms of theogony, cosmogony, and anthropogony in order to reveal an ever-emerging Godhead who encompasses all of temporal creation and, within it, human existence. The book’s ultimate implication is that Being and Nonbeing mutually participate in an ongoing process of divine coming-to-birth and dying that implicates all things, existent and nonexistent, temporal and eternal. God’s continual generation from nothing manifests the full actualization of freedom: the freedom to create ex nihilo.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aGod. 0aPhilosophical theology. 0aPostmodern theology. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  areligious studies, philosophy, agnosticism, religion, atheism, postmodrenism, contemporary theology, thinking about god, self-revelation, manifestation, renowned theologist, divine persons, the holy trinity, theogony, cosmogony, anthropogony, ever-emerging godhead, temporal creation, human existence, actualization, freedom, philosophical.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022635962540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226359762423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226359762/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles